Data type defines the type of data that a column can hold. 
Different data types: 
1.String
-------
      CHAR
      VARCHAR 
      TEXT
      ENUM 
      SET
2.Number 
-------
      INT
      BIGINT
      DECIMAL 
3.Boolean
--------
      TINYINT
      Bool
      Boolean 
4.Date 
----
    date 
    time 
    timestamp 
5.JSON
6.BLOB

1.String
-------

Char Data Type 
==============
-It is used to store fixed length alpha-numeric data. 
Syntax:
      column_name char(size) 
-When we are trying to store less number of characters than the size specified in char data type then MySQL server internally adds blank space in place of remaining
character. 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE Employee(
        		name char(20)
        );
        INSERT INTO Employee VALUES( 'Akash');
        INSERT INTO Employee VALUES( 'Ram');
        SELECT * FROM Employee;
        
        | [name] |
        | Akash  |
        | Ram    |
-If we are not giving size then default value is 1. 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE Employee1(
        		name char
        );
        DESC Employee1;
        
        | [Field] | [Type]   | [Null] | [Key] | [Default] | [Extra] |
        |  name   | char(1)  |  YES   |       |   NULL    |         |

Varchar Data Type 
------------------
It is used to store variable length alpha-numeric data. 
Syntax:
       column_name varchar(size) 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE Employee2(
        		name VArchar(50)
        );
        INSERT INTO Employee2 VALUES( 'Akash');
        INSERT INTO Employee2 VALUES( 'Ram');
        SELECT * FROM Employee2;

        | [name] |
        | Akash  |
        | Ram    |

Text data type 
--------------
-It is used to store large amounts of textual data such as article content, comments, or forum posts etc. 
Syntax:
       column_name text
-Size is not applicable. If we are providing size explicitly then MySQL will ignore.
Example:
        CREATE TABLE blog_posts (
            post_id INT,
            title VARCHAR(255),
            content TEXT
        );

Data      Type	Size
-----    ------------
CHAR	    255 bytes
VARCHAR	  ~16 KB (16383 bytes)
TEXT	    ~64 KB (65535 bytes)
LONGTEXT	~4 GB

ENUM
----
-ENUM represents a fixed set of string values.
-We can store 65,535 distinct values.
-Each ENUM has an index. Index begins with 1.
-Internally, MySQL stores the index, not the string itself.
Example:
        CREATE TABLE orders (
            order_id INT,
            status ENUM('Pending', 'Approved', 'Rejected')
        );
        INSERT INTO orders (status) VALUES ('Pending');
        INSERT INTO orders (status) VALUES ('Approved');
        INSERT INTO orders (status) VALUES ('Rejected');
        SELECT * FROM orders;
        
        | [order_id] | [status]   |
        |   NULL     | Pending    |
        |   NULL     | Approved   |
        |   NULL     | Rejected   |

SET
---
-ENUM store exactly one option from a fixed list.
-SET can store multiple options from a fixed list.
Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee_skills (
            name VARCHAR(50),
            skills SET('mysql', 'python', 'hadoop', 'linux', 'pyspark')
        );
        
        INSERT INTO employee_skills (name, skills) VALUES ('A', 'mysql,python');
        INSERT INTO employee_skills (name, skills) VALUES ('B', 'python,mysql');
        INSERT INTO employee_skills (name, skills) VALUES ('C', 'linux,pyspark');
        INSERT INTO employee_skills (name, skills) VALUES ('D', 'hadoop,pyspark');


        SELECT * FROM employee_skills WHERE skills='mysql';
        SELECT * FROM employee_skills WHERE find_in_set('mysql', skills);

        SELECT * FROM employee_skills;
        
        | [name] | [skills]        |
        |   A    | mysql,python    |
        |   B    | mysql,python    |
        |   C    | linux,pyspark   |
        |   D    | hadoop,pyspark  |

2.Number 
--------

| [Data Type]     | [Size (Bytes)] | [Maximum Value]        |
|  tinyint        |       1        | 127 (2^7 − 1)          |
|  smallint       |       2        | 32767 (2^15 − 1)       |
|  mediumint      |       3        | 8388607                |
|  int / integer  |       4        | 2147483647             |
|  bigint         |       8        | 9223372036854775807    |

int data type 
-------------
-It is used to store integers only. It does not store floating point (number with decimal value) number. 
Syntax:
       column_name int 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee3 (
            employee_id INT
        );
        
        INSERT INTO employee3 VALUES (101);
        INSERT INTO employee3 VALUES (90.3);
        INSERT INTO employee3 VALUES (90.5);
        INSERT INTO employee3 VALUES (90.7);
        INSERT INTO employee3 VALUES (9090123123); -- Not posiible it is bigint
        
        SELECT * FROM employee3
        | [employee_id] |
        |      101      |
        |      90       |
        |      91       |
        |      91       |

        CREATE TABLE employee4 (
            employee_id BIGINT
        );
        INSERT INTO employee4 VALUES (9090123123);
        SELECT * FROM employee4;
        
        |employee_id  |
        |-----------  |
        |9090123123   |

decimal data type 
-----------------
-Non integral data type has an integer part and fractional part.
-We can use NUMERIC, DECIMAL or NUMBER data type to store non integral numbers.

| Data Type           | Size (Bytes) |
|---------------------|--------------|
| Float               | 4            |
| Decimal / Numeric   | 8            |

| Topic       | Description                                                                 |
|-------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Syntax      | column_name DECIMAL(p, s)                                                    |
| Precision   | Total number of digits (both left and right of the decimal point)           |
| Scale       | Number of digits to the right of the decimal point                          |
| Rule 1      | If digits before decimal point > (p − s), an error is raised                |
| Condition 1 | number_of_digits_before_decimal_point > (p − s) → ERROR                     |
| Rule 2      | If digits after decimal point > s, MySQL rounds the value                   |
| Condition 2 | number_of_digits_after_decimal_point > s → input = ROUND(input, s)   

Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee5( 
        salary decimal(8,2) 
        );
         
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(300000.20);  
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(400000.2); 
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(4000001.2); -- Not possible
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(4000001); -- Not possible
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(400000); 
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(4000.901);
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(4000.908);
        INSERT INTO employee5 VALUES(4000.905);

        SELECT * FROM employee5;
        | salary     |
        |------------|
        | 300000.20  |
        | 400000.20  |
        | 400000.00  |
        | 4000.90    |
        | 4000.91    |

3.Boolean(Boolean/bool/TINYINT Datatype)
---------

-The Boolean/bool data type stores logical values, i.e., true or false. 
-boolean and bool data types are same. Both are aliases for the TINYINT.
Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee (
        id int,
        status boolean
        );

        INSERT INTO employee VALUES (1, TRUE);
        DESC employee;
        | Field  | Type        | Null | Key | Default | Extra |
        |--------|-------------|------|-----|---------|-------|
        | id     | int         | YES  |     | NULL    |       |
        | status | tinyint(1)  | YES  |     | NULL    |       |

        SELECT * FROM employee6;
        | id | status |
        |----|--------|
        | 1  | 1      |

4.Date Data Type
----------------
-It is used to store dates in MySQL date format. 
-It is used to store dates in the format 'YYYY-MM-DD' 
Syntax:
      column_name date 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee7( doj date);
        INSERT INTO employee7 VALUES('2024-07-12');
        INSERT INTO employee7 VALUES('12-07-2024'); -- Not posiible ('YYYY-MM-DD') correct
        
        INSERT INTO employee7 VALUES(str_to_date('12-07-2024','%d-%m-%Y'));
        
        SELECT doj FROM employee7;

        SELECT date_format(doj,'%d-%m-%Y') FROM employee7;
        | date_format(doj,'%d-%m-%Y') |
        |----------------------------|
        | 12-07-2024                 |
        | 12-07-2024                 |
        
        SELECT date_format(doj,'%m-%d-%Y') FROM employee7;
        | date_format(doj,'%m-%d-%Y') |
        |----------------------------|
        | 07-12-2024                 |
        | 07-12-2024                 |


Format Parameter 
-----------------
%Y: Year (4 digits) 
%y: Year (2 digits) 
%m: Month (01..12) 
%d: Day (01..31) 
%H: Hour (00..23) 
%h: Hour (01..12) 
%i: Minutes (00..59) 
%s: Seconds (00..59) 
%p: AM or PM 
%W: Day of the week (Sunday..Saturday) 
%M: Month name (January..December) 
%b: Abbreviated month name (Jan..Dec) 
%c: Month number (1..12) 

Time Data Type 
---------------
-It is used to store time values.  
-It represents a time of day in the format 'HH:MM:SS'. 
Syntax: 
       columnname time 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee8( intime time);
        INSERT INTO employee8 VALUES('12:24:56'); -- 'HH:MM:SS'
        
        
        INSERT INTO employee8 VALUES(str_to_date('10:11:12','%h:%i:%s'));
        INSERT INTO employee8 VALUES(str_to_date('10-11-12','%h-%i-%s'));
        
        
        SELECT intime FROM employee8;
        | intime   |
        |----------|
        | 10:11:12 |
        | 10:11:12 |
        | 10:11:12 |
        | 12:24:56 |
        
        SELECT date_format(intime,'%s:%i:%h') FROM employee8;
        | date_format(intime,'%s:%i:%h') |
        |-------------------------------|
        | 12:11:10                      |
        | 12:11:10                      |
        | 12:11:10                      |
        | 56:24:12                      |
                
        SELECT date_format(intime,'%h-%s-%i') FROM employee8;
        | date_format(intime,'%h-%s-%i') |
        |-------------------------------|
        | 10-12-11                      |
        | 10-12-11                      |
        | 10-12-11                      |
        | 12-56-24                      |

Timestamp Data Type 
-------------------
-It is used to store date and time values, including both the date and the time of day, in 
-the format 'YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS'. 
Syntax:
      column_name timestamp 
Example:
        CREATE TABLE employee9( Create_At timestamp);
        INSERT INTO employee9 VALUES('2026-01-25 02:11:54'); -- 'HH:MM:SS'
        INSERT INTO employee9 VALUES('2026/01/24 02:11:54');
        
        INSERT INTO employee9 VALUES(str_to_date('2026-23-01 10:11:12','%Y-%d-%m %h:%i:%s'));
        
        SELECT Create_At FROM employee9;
        SELECT date_format(Create_At,'%y-%d-%m %s:%i:%h') FROM employee9;

        | date_format(Create_At,'%y-%d-%m %s:%i:%h') |
        |------------------------------------------- |
        | 26-25-01 54:11:02                          |
        | 26-26-01 54:11:02                          |
        | 26-24-01 54:11:02                          |
        | 26-23-01 12:11:10                          |


5.JSON
-------
JSON (Java Script Object Notation)
Sample JSON Data
{
  "student_id": 1,
  "name": "Ram",
  "age": 20
}
Example:
        CREATE TABLE students2 (
            id INT,
            data JSON
        );
        DESC students2;
        
        | Field | Type | Null | Key | Default | Extra |
        |-------|------|------|-----|---------|-------|
        | id    | int  | YES  |     | NULL    |       |
        | data  | json | YES  |     | NULL    |       |
        
        INSERT INTO students2 VALUES(2, '{
          "student_id": 2,
          "name": "Raj",
          "age": 30
        }');
        
        SELECT * FROM students2 WHERE data->>'$.age' > 25;
        | id | data                                   |
        |----|----------------------------------------|
        | 2  | {"age": 30, "name": "Raj", "student_id": 2} |
        
        SELECT * FROM students2;
        | id | data                                   |
        |----|----------------------------------------|
        | 2  | {"age": 30, "name": "Raj", "student_id": 2} |

6.BLOB
------
-BLOB (Binary Large OBject) can store large amounts of binary data, such as images, audio, and video files.
Example:
        Create Table
        CREATE TABLE customer (
            name VARCHAR(255),
            signature BLOB
        );
Insert Record:
              INSERT INTO customer VALUES ('Ram', LOAD_FILE('"C:\Users\DELL\OneDrive\Pictures\Camera Roll\IMG_20241013_005435_030.webp"'));
              
              SELECT * FROM customer;
              | name | signature |
              |------|-----------|
              | Ram  | NULL      |



































